<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ871210-0055 </DOCNO><HL> Mark Stahl SentencingIs Postponed to Feb. 5</HL><DD> 12/10/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> SHE AXPSECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR) </IN><DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sentencing was postponed until Feb. 5 for Mark Stahl, a former senior vice president, finance, at Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc. who pleaded guilty in June to a check-kiting scheme.    Mr. Stahl, who is free on a $1 million bond, admitted to misappropriating company funds in a scheme that prosecutors said involved $19 million.    He could be sentenced to as long as 20 years in prison and fined a maximum of $1 million for the four felony wire-fraud counts to which he pleaded guilty.    Sentencing by Federal Judge Vincent L. Broderick originally was scheduled for last Tuesday. </TEXT></DOC>